# Context: a stray `import` placed AFTER a declaration is invalid Go ("imports
# must appear before other declarations"). gsx treats Go as an opaque blob, so
# this used to be caught only when the assembled skeleton was parsed, with the
# skeleton's //line directives mapping the error back to the .gsx origin.
#
# func render()'s body embeds an element (`<div>inline JSX</div>`), so this
# whole region — including both imports — is one *GoWithElements decl, never a
# plain *GoChunk. checkReservedDecls now parses every top-level Go region (via
# goWithElementsSrc's byte-length-preserving reconstruction) BEFORE the skeleton
# is built, so it is the one that hits this parse failure and reports it,
# positioned directly in the .gsx by plain byte-offset arithmetic — the skeleton
# is never assembled for this file, and skeletonParseError never runs. The
# reported position (9:1) is unchanged from before that pass existed only
# because both mechanisms compute the same .gsx offset for this input; unlike
# the plain-GoChunk cases (xpkg/interleaved_imports_error,
# goexpr-f-literal/js_value_unsupported), whose positions actually improved —
# from block-relative splitChunk output to real .gsx positions — in the same
# change (commit 87556d8).
-- input.gsx --
package demo

import "github.com/gsxhq/gsx"

func render() gsx.Node {
	return <div>inline JSX</div>
}

import "strings"

component Index() {
	<section>{ render() }</section>
}
-- diagnostics.golden --
9:1: imports must appear before other declarations
